occupation: Research Engineer at South 8 Technologies
headline: Research Engineer at South 8 Technologies
summary:
Even after 3 years of researching and engineering batteries I still find them almost magical. They are essentially nanoscale sponges absorbing practically invisible lithium-ions at the thermodynamic and kinetic limits of the liquid soup of electrolyte transporting them and continue to excite both me for the science and an insanely rapid growing market for their capabilities and hope of a greener future.

In my current role as a Research Engineer, I get to directly study that magic by researching and developing South 8 Technologies' novel liquefied gas (LiGas) electrolyte ranging from testing various electrolyte formulations/additives to optimizing for specific electrodes or use cases. Concurrently, I help train and educate Research Associates on cell construction and electrochemistry fundamentals, as well as direct cell builds for various projects. I have experience using and interpreting data from cyclic voltametry (CV), electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS), conductivity measurements and general battery cycling (life cycle, rate and temperature capabilities) on Biologic and Maccor cyclers.

I've also had experience conducting UL safety testing, including thermal runaway, temperature, short circuit and overcharge/discharge testing of both modules and packs used in electric vehicles during my time at Flux Power. During my graduate studies, I also extensively studied lithium metal anodes, first authoring a paper on optical in-situ characterization of lithium plating and stripping, took multiple courses on electrochemistry and materials at UC San Diego and established and effectively managed a battery lab at SDSU.

My background in Mechanical Engineering has also provided a unique ability to critically solve problems through engineering and building practical solutions that are not always available commercially.

As I continue to grow in my career, I hope to keep learning about the world of electrochemical devices, research and develop interesting new technologies, educate and lead the next generation of innovators and researchers and ultimately help contribute to a greener and cleaner future for us all.

occupation: Information Technology Support Specialist at US Navy
headline: Network Support Specialist at US Navy
summary:
Hello potential boss!
I'll "BLUF" (Bottom line up front) this by saying openly that I have ADHD, so my apologies for the tangential, wordy mess that will be most of what you read here.

I was born May 21st, 1992 in Richfield, Utah to my father Bret Baum and my mother Laurie Mitchell. I have two siblings, both sisters born June 19th, 1990 and September 6th, 1993. Raised within 30 miles of my hometown. Absolutely enjoyed/excelled at math (geometry, trig, algebra, calculus) and physics growing up. Would love to eventually go to college to get a degree in astrophysics, quantum mechanics, add infinitum. 

I love learning new information about almost anything and am a wealth of random knowledge, but my favorites are physics/software technology, the world, universe. I love learning how everything works down to a base/component level and almost whenever posed with a question about any of the above, I will try to find the answer by any means (books, YouTube, Google etc). If I need to know something to complete a task and don't, or just want to know more information, Google or YouTube. If I believe it to possibly be in the public domain and I don't know how something works or how to do something, I will without shame open Google and search until I find it, or sufficient searches have been done to show it is not easily obtainable through those channels in which case I will turn to a supervisor. Some would tell me to do that first, but supervisors have their own jobs and I feel it unfair to bother them with a question at my level if I couldn't be bothered to do the initial search for the answer myself. All that being said I don't believe everything I see or hear and will frequently try to find multiple sources dictating the same info before stating it with confidence. 

Mental Health issues may take my mind off track every once in a while but if I hyper-focus on a task, and am given the breathing space to execute, I will perform on average better than my peers. Some of my strengths would be attentiveness to detail, my adaptation to change, and my adequate timeliness on competing tasks. I'm usually in the top 2-3 performers when viewing technical job performance (servers, printers, workstations, switches/routers, basic IT/work related knowledge etc). My weaknesses would be effective direct (face to face) communication as I usually need to preface conversations before I have them, my inability to accept change for the sake of change, and my work-arrival timeliness as some of my health conditions make my sleep patterns variable, especially when on regular shifts.

occupation: Software Engineer II at Wave
headline: Software Engineer II at Wave
summary:
Ever since being given a book on MSWLogo at 7 in a flimsy attempt by my dad to get me out of his hair, I've been programming games. While my early attempts were fairly lackluster, I moved quickly to Python, to Game Maker, to Flash and AS3, and finally to Unity, leaving a trail of passionate attempts at entertainment media in my wake. At Becker College I was able to develop my skills with industry experience, working on several commercial mobile titles with MassDiGI. My crowning achievement at Becker, as far as I'm concerned, was CyberDrive 2077 - I developed this game from scratch with a team of six at MassDiGI SIP 2018, continued on as producer and lead programmer to take it to launch, and it went on to become one of our most successful titles in the history of MassDiGI, with thousands of players and a 4.7 star rating on the App Store. 

Since summer 2019, I've worked heavily with Dejobaan Games, the award-winning developers of Elegy for a Dead World, Monster Loves You!, and AaAaAA!!! – A Reckless Disregard for Gravity. I helped bring Twenty Minute Metropolis, a 3D city builder released in March 2019, to a procedurally-generated 2D isometric prototype of a sequel, Thirty Minute Metropolis. My shader expertise, refined in my work with 30MM, helped Dejobaan take their visual style for Last Night on Planet Earth from Photoshop mockups to realtime Unity scenes. I'm currently working on a remaster of AaAaAA!!!, Dejobaan's 2009 hit basejumping game, putting my graphics programming skills to the task of updating the visuals to pristine 2020 quality.

Since graduation, I've worked for Tricky Fast Studios, a Massachusetts-based contract development firm, providing development support to AAA game projects and sophisticated interactive products. In just a short period, I've had the opportunity to work on a wide variety of projects, in a variety of development situations.

occupation: Lithography Engineer at Intel Corporation
headline: Lithography for HVM | Physical Chemist Ph.D. UCSB
summary:
Have you ever been unable to choose between two conflicting interests? My academic interest can be understood through a drive to bridge science and physical, cultural history as a scientist whose interests are driven by a strong background in archiving and anthropology. As a Ph.D. student in physical chemistry at UC Santa Barbara, I am using the research field of gas phase spectroscopy and mass spectrometry to investigate cultural questions such as 'What did the ancient Mayans drink?" and "What does that knowledge tell me about their culture?" Using modern analysis techniques with low limits of detection and high sensitivity, we are able to quantify drink residues in pottery fragments from the Mayan era in order to understand the class stratification and diverse trade networks.

Fields like anthropology or archeology often seek to understand the multifaceted complexities of defining and understanding a community through the analysis of personal experience, observation, written record, and conversation. Scientific tools and approaches often can support these narratives and expedite our narrative construction. I believe that scientific methods can serve as better tools to illuminate history and aid minority and disadvantaged groups commonly neglected in society’s narratives. 

The collaboration of analytical scientific techniques with experts in the fields of art and archeology to dictate the effect of these findings on cultural narratives, is the focus of my Ph.D. and hopefully of my larger career.

I am a tool builder, and I have been from the very outset of my career. I came out of school with a degree in architectural engineering, and immediately went to work for a company producing software tools for the design and analysis of architectural lighting systems. Since those early days, I have steadily honed my craft to produce software of uncompromising accuracy, speed, and directness of usability.

The best tools are built by those who use tools. My early work in non-imaging optical analysis software was born of my work in designing life-critical lighting systems for the operating table. Today, I spend hundreds of hours a year engaged in digital astrophotography. This hobby has yielded dozens of techniques, algorithms, and usability ideas that feed my professional work of building sophisticated analytics to extract insight from geospatial imagery and related data.

As my career has matured, I have developed the skill of operating at higher levels of abstraction, evolving from software engineer to software architect. Today, my favorite challenges usually center on taking on a complex problem, identifying big picture patterns, and organizing an effective blend of new and existing technology to meet the challenge.  I have a gift for deconstructing and explaining complex problems clearly, but I also still enjoy getting down to the “nitty-gritty” details to solve those problems.  

When I’m not building software or processing astrophotography images, I enjoy travelling, mountaineering here in Colorado, listening to and learning about music, and going on long bike rides.

The word “Engineering” seems complicated and difficult to comprehend to most; however, for me, I see it as a means of expressing my creativity to the problem and the solution is the art.

College is similar in a way, we are given a set of problems from our professors to find our creativity to the problem and how each student approach the problem was different. These differences could lead to innovations that could greatly impact the world.

For my first professional project, I was allowed to develop an alternative to Continuous positive airway pressure (CPAP). This is what keeps me going, an endless cycle that will continuously create innovation.

The most important thing that school has taught me is that education is a means to an end, we must always pursue what each value as important. Most importantly, in my life, I see that I majored in mechanical and electrical engineering to broaden my creativity to approach the problem and this will help me become someone who is inspiring.

occupation: Sr. Building Envelope Consultant at Sullivan Engineering, A Rimkus Company
headline: Sr. Building Envelope Consultant at Sullivan Engineering, A Rimkus Company
summary:
I remember the first book my dad bought me. It was written in Indonesian and literally translated to “Tell Me Why”.  The book contained simple explanations to questions that children ask, such as “Why is the ocean so salty”, or “What is the difference between a fruit and a vegetable”.  Having this book read to me, ignited a sense of curiosity in me since I was little which has never died since.

Now how do I harness this curiosity?  I decided to focus my career in forensics engineering! Interweaving it with my interest in buildings and architecture, I specialise in understanding the root causes and mechanisms that lead to the failures of components and/or systems in the built environment.

Throughout my career, I have inspected over 300 distinct buildings, ranging from single-storey residential dwellings in the outback, to one of the highest residential apartment building in Australia.

The types of issues that I have diagnosed and repaired, includes the following (to name a few):

	- Interior and exterior waterproofing membranes
	- Combustible cladding
	- Building movements induced by reactive clay soils
	- Concrete reinforcement spalling 
	- Glazing elements
	- Lightweight cladding
	- Parking garages

I am not your regular engineer.  I'm a very visual person and love utilising sketches and diagrams to depict my ideas.  This includes hand-drawn details to computer models for clients and contractors alike.  I am naturally outgoing and have a high level of personal energy!  I love coordination, sharing experiences, and knowledge with others around me which makes me thrive in teams.   

When I am not crawling under buildings or hanging out the side of skyscrapers, I enjoy practicing and competing in Brazilian Jiu Jitsu, cooking, and reading.

I love a good chat - so don't hesitate to reach out.

I am an experimental physics Ph.D. student the University of California, Santa Barbara.  My research interests dominantly lie in quantum transport and terahertz/mm-wave excitations of 2D quantum materials, primarily graphene and transition metal dichalcogenides. My unique and extensive academic and industrial background in electrical engineering, microwave and terahertz electromagnetics, and solid state electronic devices allows to me push the capabilities of modern measurements into the next age. 

I am also a development engineer at Lake Shore Cryotronics. I seek to develop and use new techniques and technologies to both simplify and further scientific endeavors at the global scale. I am interested in mixing raw physics and engineering with modern electronic instruments to turn standalone tools into platforms for probing cutting-edge physics. 

My personal website: http://web.physics.ucsb.edu/~ampotts/

My interest in early childhood education first stemmed from my own educational experience. As a child, I was always encouraged to value my education and to never lose my curiosity to learn more about the world around me. That curiosity then helped me realize how important a child's education is in the early phases of life, which is why I am now a pre-school teacher. My teaching method also stems from this source of curiosity. At the early stages of childhood, all children are extremely curious about the world around them. I then foster that curiosity and use auditory, visual and linguistic teaching methods to help the child further develop the necessary skills they'll need in life and their educational journeys.

I am committed to my students and their families and hope to provide a safe and peaceful environment for them to learn and grow together.

occupation: Research Scientist at zeroK NanoTech
headline: Research Scientist at zeroK NanoTech
summary:
I am presently a Postdoctoral Fellow working at the startup company zeroK NanoTech.  My current research is on the application of atomic physics and laser cooling techniques to the development of a cold ion source for focused ion beam (FIB) instruments.  We are collaborating with the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) Center for Nanoscale Science and Technology (CNST) on this project.  My appointment at zeroK NanoTech is enabled by the Small Business Postdoctoral Research Diversity Fellowship from the American Society of Engineering Education (ASEE); this is an NSF-supported fellowship.

In my other recent research I have studied rubidium atoms in highly excited electronic states, known as Rydberg states.  In early 2014 I used their sensitivity to electromagnetic fields to develop an atom-based sensing technique for RF and mm-wave electric fields.  This work was in collaboration with researchers at NIST, Boulder.  In my Ph.D. thesis work I studied the interactions between Rydberg atoms.  These are relevant to quantum information processing, and also play a role in energy transfer in atomic gases.

According to all known information and Wikipedia; Spades was devised in the United States in the late 1930s and became popular in the 1940s. The game's rise to popularity in the U.S. came during World War II, when it was introduced by soldiers from its birthplace in Cincinnati, Ohio. (Wikipedia.com). Presently, Spades has an expansive online gaming community. Spades is not only a strategic game but, creates a bond between partners that one never forgets. Decisive Advocates and The success of failure movement would love to introduce this to our community wide by having awesome, well organized, internal networking spades tournaments. 
Decisive Advocates & The Success of Failure presents: A Spades tournament.  This Spades tournament will be held at the Shore Culture Center 291 East 222nd street Euclid, Ohio 44123 on November 18th, 2017 from 4:00 pm -7:30 pm. Individuals can enter the tournament as a single entry or a team of two. If you enter as an single entry your partner will be auto picked for you.  We will have   a non-tournament entry to come and connect with the community! We will have music, semi and finalist prizes, game judges, music, great food and more. Most importantly, over One hundred individuals can enter the Spades tournament to play against some great spades players. 
A Spades Tournament can be a great networking opportunity for your business, school, movement and self. We have different companies that will be present to support their sponsored teams as well. 
This unique event and opportunity to connect is the reason we’ve created this tournament right here in our hometown. Come out and join us.  We cannot wait to see you! For more information or immediate sponsorships go to Decisiveadvocates.com or A_ Spades_ Tournament on Instagram/ A Spades Tournament on Facebook, Twitter, and LinkedIn. Entry for A Spades Tournament is online at  https://www.eventbrite.com/e/a-spades-tournament-tickets-38203926974
 or by calling 800-605-5074 ex 801.

occupation: Consultant I Facilitator at EnGen Collaborative, LLC
headline: Advocate, Facilitator, Collaborator I Gender & Climate Resilience
summary:
A professional with more than 15 years’ experience in program management, donor relations, and stakeholder engagement. Background in gender equity and climate advocacy with the United Nations, U.S. Government and grassroots leaders. Experience in international development, strategic partnerships, event planning, and policy analysis.  

At the Sierra Club, I designed and launched the first-ever gender equity program at a national environmental organization.  We built a program based on the foundation that no matter one's gender we all deserve access to clean air and water, health care and safety. Within the first 18 months we garnered more than 100,000 dedicated online action takers from all 50 states. The program worked to protect the lives and health of women and LGBTQ communities so we can be resilient, healthy and effective leaders in our communities. This included access to paid family leave, reproductive rights, protection from gender based violence, toxics-free products, and integration of feminist principles into national and global climate policy.  

My previous work includes advocacy on the United Nations sustainable development goals, training governments and NGOs on women’s health and climate change in East Africa and Southeast Asia, and managing a portfolio of sub-grants totaling more than $500,000 across 8 countries. I served on the board of the Global Gender and Climate Alliance, as a program manger for a network of women environmental philanthropists, Rachel's Network, and worked as a policy fellow for the U.S. House Select Committee on Energy Independence & Global Warming in the aftermath of the 2010 BP oil spill. I am a regular contributor to Ms. Magazine, Huffington Post and Woodrow Wilson Center’s New Security Beat. 

My interest in global gender, health and environment was cultivated during my time in Latin America -- through volunteer work with USAID programs in Bolivia and the Ministry of Environment in Chile. During that period I also founded a dental health education program, Project Risa, which provided dental health education and a total of 10,000 dental supplies to children across the region, partnering with Engineers without Border, Caritas and others. 

My love for community organizing and event planning took shape in my own DC neighborhood. In 2016 I was elected as an Advisory Neighborhood Commissioner (ANC 1C04) in the Adams Morgan neighborhood of Washington D.C. where - for eight years - I also coordinated a large-scale music and arts festival, Adams Morgan Day, with 30,000 attendees annually.

occupation: Professor at University of Wisconsin Oshkosh
headline: Co-Founder, Algoma Algal Biotechnology LLC, Professor, Microbial Genetics & Biotechnology, Univ. Wisconsin - Oshkosh
summary:
Toivo Kallas is a Distinguished Professor of Microbial Genetics and Biotechnology at the University of Wisconsin – Oshkosh. He has a B.A. from Carleton College, Northfield, MN, a Ph.D. in Microbiology from the University of Oregon, and postdoctoral training from the Institut Pasteur and University of California – Berkeley. He has spent sabbaticals at the Institut Biologie Physico-Chimique (Paris) and UW Madison Biotechnology Center to investigate photosynthetic energy conversion and environmental responses of microalgae. He has over 30 years of experience in research on electron transfer protein complexes, energy transduction, and gene expression in cyanobacteria. More than 70 undergraduate students, 23 Master’s students, and several post-doctoral and visiting scientists have participated in this research funded by grants from the NSF, USDA, UW Oshkosh, and the UW System WiSys Technology Foundation. 

Since 2010 he and Matthew Nelson have joined forces with Eric Singsaas (UWSP and WIST) to engineer cyanobacteria (blue-green algae) to efficiently convert solar energy, CO2, and wastewaters into 1) algal biomass for animal and fish feeds and 2) isoprene-terpene chemicals for bioproducts and biofuels. The team has a patent pending and in 2012 founded Algoma Algal Biotechnology (AABT) LLC to commercialize this venture. AABT's technology and development is currently funded by an NSF-STTR Phase I grant and a UW Center for Technology Commercialization SBIR-Advance supplement for business development.

occupation: BUS-K 303 Business Analytics Peer Tutor at Indiana University - Kelley School of Business
headline: Kelley Finance Major | French Minor | Director of Finance at DPhiE | Business Analytics and Statistics Peer Tutor | Founder of MHM at RHA | Professional Bharatanatyam Dancer
summary:
A diligent leader and driven learner, I aspire to be an impactful part of the financial community in the future. I have always been curious about the market, investment portfolios and finance in general. What recently interested me is the CAPM (Capital Asset Pricing Model) model and its assumption of the market being on the tangency portfolio. This is just a model, however its implications really intrigue me. 

Having learned an Indian classical dance form for over ten years has really helped me with discipline. I have been able to acquire skills like being focused, dedicated, having patience and communication skills. What I always appreciated, not just with regards to my dance, is criticism. I believe I am a good listener because I truly feel that everyone you meet knows something you don’t and it’s always beneficial to get to know yourself from different perspectives. There is always room for improvement and I usually push myself and everyone around me beyond limits and this is something that motivates me to take charge, and to mentor. 

My love for mentoring grew due to my constant urge of being surrounded by new people and helping them in any way that I can. Since I was kid, I have loved contributing to the society and have been a part of many different community service activities - from organizing weekly educational drives to organizing Relay For Life in my high school. As the founder of the Menstrual Hygiene Management program at the Robin Hood Army, I was able to spread awareness about a very important yet basic topic to the underprivileged. My main focus was to educate young girls and to remove the taboo associated with it.

I look for mentoring opportunities everywhere I go because I view them as the most efficient learning opportunities. Being a peer tutor for Business Analytics and Statistics has helped me to explore those subject areas even further. Microsoft Excel is my best friend and being a peer tutor significantly aided me when I was the Director of Finance at my sorority. 

Due to my liking of building connections and meeting people, I have also been fascinated by how business build relationships with different areas in the world, apart from just financial ones. I was effectively able to explore this inclination of mine further when I analyzed public relations while I interned at Bliss GVS Pharma. 

Looking ahead, I would love to explore all my interests being part of a financial institution. I aspire to continue my research on tangency market portfolios and would love to help people make the right decisions with investment portfolios!

headline: CFO Coach for Small Businesses | Strategic Profit Growth Expert | Cash Management | Projections | Data Analysis & Visualization | Empowering Entrepreneurs to understand the power of numbers in running their business
summary:
Inspired by family.

Empowered by numbers.

𝗠𝘆 𝗺𝗶𝘀𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗶𝘀 𝘀𝗶𝗺𝗽𝗹𝗲 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗶𝘁 𝘀𝘁𝗮𝗿𝘁𝘀 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝗮 𝗿𝗲𝗮𝗹 𝘀𝘁𝗼𝗿𝘆… 
My financial career started at my parent’s grocery store, at the grand age of 9. I was supposed to sit at the front of the store and sell ice-cream. My official title was Ice Cream Fridge Manager. In all fairness, I ate more than I sold, but I did learn everything about cash management.

My dad also taught me about gross profit margins. Eat less and sell more, he said. But a good start nonetheless.

As a minority in Montenegro, oppression and injustice were commonplace, but my parents’ determination to keep the business going was what inspired me to learn all the financial know-how to keep the business and my family together. Nearly 2 decades later their strength continues to inspire me to help other businesses shine and continue on their mission to do good in the world.

If you are an entrepreneur ready for growth, are you able to answer the following questions: 

✔ Do you 𝗞now the company's cash needs six months out?
✔ Are you 𝗔ble to grow bottom line profitability 3-5% year over year?
✔ Do you know 𝗥eal project profit margins?
✔ Do you know 𝗘xact dollar break-even point?

If no, then reach out to me for: 
Strategic financial management | Quantitative analysis | Financial Forecasting 

I am happy to speak at events focused on diversity and inclusion in finance. Reach out here or through my website www.karecfo.com.

occupation: Mechanical Design Engineer at Avery Dennison
headline: Mechanical Design Engineer at Avery Dennison
summary:
Through Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE), I have developed my social, organizational, and leadership skills.  Being the mechanical lead of SAE Aero has taught me so much more than I ever would have expected about engineering.  I get to experience first hand that engineering is a social and collaborative field, and that your projects are only as strong as all the people involved.  No one person can design, test, and manufacture great engineering tech, and I try to show my team that all the work that they do is important.   

This is one reason why I love engineering.  Great engineers often are stereotyped as the socially awkward, quiet genius, and while many of us may be a bit socially awkward, I have learned that true engineering is not just one person quietly punching numbers on his calculator, it is many people who work hard and work together to accomplish their goals.

Technology is so amazing to me, and I love being involved in this field.  My goal for the future involved in amazing projects.  That is why I am interested in Aviation and Aerospace.  I want to be part of something that takes us off of the ground.  It is mind bending to me how humans have been able to create technology that even leaves our atmosphere, and it would be my dream to be a part of that.

I am the kind of person who loves to learn, and loves a challenge.  Some of my hardest classes in my educational career have been the classes that I tend to do the best at, and I would not have been able to do it without collaborating with my piers.  Conquering difficult challenges, as a group, to me that is engineering.

occupation: SMB Optimization & Scaling Consultant at SMB Optimization & Scaling
headline: If you're a small business owner and if you're not seeing the results you're working hard to get, we need to talk: I might have a couple of ideas for you!
summary:
Helping someone and watching them evolve is what gets me up every day!
Whether it was a business or an individual, technology or strategy, work or leisure, that sense of achievement is unmatched.

Technology and sports are where it all started: You should've seen the huge smile on my face winning my first match, the exhilaration I felt when someone I helped wins the match, the awe when meeting the new IBM XT, and the happiness and wonder when playing with the Commodore 64.

First I see potential, then I start immediately thinking of ways to achieve that potential, finally, I try to make it a reality and strive to take it a step further…

I started my professional career writing software and building networks while selling ads and event tickets on the side. Freelancing forced me to find effective ways to manage my customers' projects and guided me towards learning the principles of project management. This presented more opportunities to me and I started to withdraw from technical work and focus more on project management.

However, I needed more: I needed to talk to more people, to meet new people, to have the flexibility to do business in and out of my desk! That's when I moved to sales.
Yet, nothing topped that exhilarating feeling I got every time I assist or coach a team member - which lead me to where I am today.

Are you ready to transform your business and evolve it to the next level? Achieve more with less? Or, perhaps, diversify your business venues?
Do you feel let down by the way business is being conducted or by some unproductive traditions in the organization?

I work with business owners and executives using a healthy mix of global standards and proven technologies to help them realize their goals.

occupation: Graduate Student Research Assistant at University of Colorado Boulder
headline: Incoming PhD candidate at Virginia Tech's Center for Power Electronics Systems (CPES) | Graduate Research Assistant at CU Boulder's Colorado Power Electronics Center (CoPEC)
summary:
After working with Autodata for 4 years and having sought CU Boulder's rigor in advanced circuit analysis from Prof. Maksimovic, I will be joining Prof. Cvetkovic and Prof. Boroyevich from Virginia Tech's Center for Power Electronics Systems (CPES) towards pursuing a PhD in wide operating range controls for high wattage power density converters.

Skillset:

Power converter control design and simulation:
• Researching source material for advocating topologies specific to an application.
• Simulating a topology’s open and closed loop operation in PSIM, MATLAB and Simulink with Zero-Order-Hold (ZOH), unit delay of PWM, induced ground bounce and step changes in load.
• Validating control laws and digital filters written in embedded C and tested in PSIM before deploying to DSP.

Converter topology deployment:
• Developing driver solutions for IGBTs, employing VCE saturation protection scheme using pulse transformers and high slew rate OP-AMP ICs for fast gate turn-on and turn-off times, without degrading the integrity of software deadband.
• Troubleshooting power device failures and taking necessary action in drive circuits along with writing immediate stopgaps in DSP in case of component scarcity or man-power absence.

Analog instrumentation and embedded target:
• Developing instrumentation for AC and DC signals for closing feedback control loops, comparator-based protections, DSP sampling, zero crossing techniques and grid synchronization.
• Prototyping common-ground and galvanic isolation-based circuits with trade-off between response times and signal quality, employing active filtering circuits and isolation amplifiers.
• Bare metal coding with assembly instructions SPI, I2C and UART for reading multiple Digital Inputs (DIs), energizing contactors for disabling soft-start (and other DOs), storing time stamped alarms in EEPROM for communication with master control unit or similar slave power modules in a redundant n+1 parallel power supply system and for RTCs.
• Writing drivers for industrial communication protocols like MODBUS RTU over RS485 lines. Also learning to build MODBUS RTU to MODBUS TCP-IP converter.

DSP algorithm validation and coding:
• Developing and optimizing controllers in assembly language based on forward, backward and bilinear transformation of analog compensators with varied integrator saturation schemes.
• Writing floating point FIR and IIR filters in 32-bit DSPs based on bilinear transformation with frequency warping of analog filters for filtering signal with ground bounce noise sampled at 2xFSW, between ringing intervals.

If you are looking for a new IT opportunity or know someone who is (we pay referral bonuses), please email me at ardy.akhzari@roberthalf.com or call me directly at (916) 302-7503.

In addition to my work at Robert Half, I'm also the Founder & Executive Director of PacksforColdBacks 501(c)3, a Sacramento-based nonprofit that provides essential survival supplies, rehabilitation services, and housing to homeless communities in California, Arizona, and Washington. Since starting Packs for Cold Backs in 2011, I have been responsible for guiding program development, fundraising, and volunteer recruitment to further increase the impact of PFCB’s services. I am passionate about social justice, racial equity, mental health, and creating an equitable future for the communities we serve. 

I also serve as the Co-Chair of the  Racial Equity Committee at Sacramento Steps Forward. Our goal with the establishment of this committee is to uncover the scope, causes, and potential solutions of race serving as a predictor for homelessness in Sacramento. Our main focus of the Racial Equity Committee is to develop an action plan to be utilized by the CoC and Sacramento County over the next three to five years to create equitable access for the most vulnerable members of our communities. With the completion of this plan, we look forward to advising other cities and states across the nation in the creation of similar programs to address racial equity, social justice, and other diversity and inclusion initiatives.

occupation: Research Associate at Biozentrum, University of Basel
headline: Senior Scientist at Biozentrum, University of Basel
summary: I am a biophysicist and electron microscopist who loves to explore the nanoscale world of cells and tissues in situ at as closest to native state as possible. I believe in all the advanced technologies(hardware and software) we have now and we will have in the future but human power will remain the central player. Here are some lines about myself: I studied physics at the University of Birzeit in West Bank, Palestine. I completed my dissertation in 2004 at the University of Lausanne with the Nobel Laureate, Jacques Dubochet. During my PhD work, I developed and applied cryo-electron microscopy of vitreous sections (CEMOVIS) on various biological specimens to study macromolecular complexes such as intercellular adhesion junctions in situ. In 2005, I moved to the European Molecular Biology Laboratory, Heidelberg and worked as a postdoctoral fellow, where I continued to investigate the molecular structure of human epidermal desmosomes using cryo-electron tomography of vitreous sections. In 2010, I moved to Bonn to take up a position as a research group leader at German Center for Neurodegenerative Diseases in cryo-electron microscopy and tomography of synapses in mouse retina. There, I spent much time doing image processing and have learned a lot of new techniques such as sub-tomogram averaging and use them to unravel the molecular architecture of retina photoreceptor rhodopsins and specialized synapses, termed ribbon synapses. Since January 2018 I am working at Center for Cellular Imaging and NanoAnalytics (C-CINA) in Basel with Henning Stahlberg where we are investigating neurodegeneration using advanced biophysical and imaging techniques. I am back again to Switzerland to the true joy, to the lab bench and experiments like it was in Lausanne more than 15 years ago; it is just much more fun!

occupation: Consultant at Wolters Kluwer
headline: Director of Informatics, Department of Anesthesiology at UCI Health; CEO, Synesthesia Associates
summary:
Aalap Shah, MD is a board-certified anesthesiologist, specializing in general adult and pediatric anesthesiology. He attended medical school at the University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine, thereafter completing a general anesthesiology residency at the University of Washington and fellowship at Boston Children’s Hospital/Harvard Medical School and obtaining certification in Lean and Six Sigma methodology. Prior to UCI, Dr. Shah provided clinical anesthesia and independent consulting services for local hospitals, ambulatory surgical centers (ASCs) and dental offices, as well as administrative services to community hospitals and medical spas in Los Angeles. 

Dr. Shah is passionate about introducing process improvement strategies in the perioperative healthcare arena, in the pursuit of simultaneously improving physician autonomy while achieving the best possible post-operative outcomes for his patients. He has published in peer-reviewed journals on topics including nerve injury, perioperative compliance measures and communication tools, and institution-level quality improvement initiatives. He also contributes op-ed pieces and has appeared on several podcasts and physician media outlets including KevinMD. He is a recipient of the ACGME David Leach Award for his leadership with a multidisciplinary team in improving communication between teams after surgery.

At UCI, Dr. Shah teaches resident trainees in the operating room with a focus on neonatal and pediatric anesthesia and lectures on anesthesia practice management. He is the Informatics Director and involved in several projects related to conservation and sustainability, quality improvement reporting, and clinical decision-support tools. Dr. Shah’s current research interests focus on “minimally invasive” therapies, including the study of music as a therapeutic modality as well as nanoanesthesia.

headline: Design Engineer at BKF Engineers, EIT
summary:
As a product of the Oakland Unified School District, Aaliyah Douglas graduated from Oakland Technical High School in 2014 and graduated from the University of California, Berkeley with a Bachelor of Science Degree in Civil and Environmental Engineering in 2018.

Aaliyah's interest in engineering began with a trip to Athens, Greece in 2009 when she was competing in track and field at the International Children's Games. Upon exploring the city, she found inspiration and motivation among the ancient buildings that remained standing after centuries of varying environmental factors. With this inspiration, she went on to enroll in the Engineering Academy offered by her high school where she learned skills such as manual technical drafting and various AutoCAD programs. In addition, further motivation was derived from her desire to explore her passion in the STEM field that students from underrepresented communities do not pursue as often due to lack of resources and support.

With that inspiration and motivation, Aaliyah made sure to have a part in giving back to UC Berkeley's surrounding community by joining the Black Engineering and Science Students Association on Berkeley's campus. One of Aaliyah's goals is to travel around the world and share her experiences as a growing and developing Civil Engineer, especially with more underrepresented communities. Her goal is to explore methods and technologies to improve transportation around the world that would help bring society into a more renewable, preventative, and progressive era. She hopes that through traveling and understanding the human experience from people of different communities that she can provide the best technology and resources possible for life improvement.

occupation: Graduate Student at University of Nebraska-Lincoln
headline: Student at University of Nebraska-Lincoln
summary:
The exponential increase in omics data availability over the past decade has allowed for the utilization of computational methods to capture the complexity of biological systems, with the goal of understanding and advancing the applications of these systems. In this regard, genome-scale metabolic reconstructions have shown promising results, generating constraint-based and kinetic models that are capable of both describing the system, and hypothesizing potential genetic interventions to optimize cellular function. 

My role in the SSbio lab is to utilize the mathematical and computational tools of optimization to construct steady state and kinetic models of metabolic networks. My first project involves working on a compartmentalized metabolic model of the maize kernel, where separate metabolic networks of the major tissue types in kernel are constructed and integrated to form a comprehensive model of the kernel. My second project involves constructing a kinetic model of sphingolipid metabolism in Arabidopsis leaves. Kinetic models are capable of capturing regulatory interactions in the network and are therefore very useful in understanding cellular responses to perturbations in the system.

occupation: 4th Grade DLI Teacher at West Contra Costa Unified School District
headline: Elementary Educator/Researcher/Social and Restorative Justice Practitioner
summary:
As an educator-leader and an experienced curriculum adopter, my passion is to create meaningful learning experiences for students with multicultural backgrounds, while addressing their social, emotional, psychological and academic potential. Early in my educational career, I decided to pursue a Master’s Degree in Cross-Cultural teaching, because I knew it would give me a perspective on educational pedagogy that emphasized compassion, equity and diversity as its center guiding posts. 

Now that I’m a doctoral student in educational leadership for social justice, my goal is to use my research skills to improve programs and create systems that address the needs of all our teachers and students. My dissertation topic focuses on teacher trauma, healing and resiliency. This is a very personal and important topic for me because it seeks to understand the learning context teachers navigate and how we can create systems of support and encouragement. As teacher induction program assistant, I intend to use my research skills to implement trauma informed practices as guiding principles for creating teacher centered supports.

My 24 year educational tenure in public schools across California,  has taught me that the most important ingredient in creating healthy and sustainable programs is to listen to teachers and grant them the opportunity to have a say in the decisions made for their classrooms. Teachers need to feel empowered, and when they do, they thrive.  This is why it is so important to implement frameworks of healing, justice, compassion, restoration and love that prioritize the needs of our educators. 

As an educator leader,  I’ve volunteered for several committees and adjunct leadership roles that have further fueled my interest in transitioning into educational leadership positions. Among some of these roles include: Dual Language Chair, Union Representative, Curriculum Committee Adopter, Units of Study Lead, after school Math Coordinator, Science Coordinator, Technology Presenter (Riverside Consortium),  ILT member, Technology Committee Member and EL grade level lead. Serving on various platforms, while teaching in the classroom, has applied my perspective on how educational systems work from the ground up. It is this same interest in leadership that led me to pursue a  preliminary administrative credential at UCI. Through my training, I learned the complexities and intricate work administrators do in order to keep a school and programs moving forward.

occupation: Marketing Strategist at Avalaunch Media
headline: Marketing Strategist | Events Planning Pro | World Traveler | Competitive Triathlete
summary:
2022 represents my 18th year working in traditional and/or digital marketing advising clients on their strategy and helping to execute that strategy.
My career began in radio in 2004 when I was still a junior in college. I was hired to conduct advertising sales and I would be ALLOWED to call play by play for high school football, basketball, soccer and baseball games for a small 1,000 watt day time only AM radio station in Blacksburg, VA.
I developed in that career for 12 years landing in 2011 as the Sports Director for Cumulus Media in Myrtle Beach, SC. I was the program director for two sports talk radio stations and the host of our morning drive talk show. I called myself a sports broadcaster but I sold my own clients ads on my show, planned events, wrote social media posts, developed websites and developed content every day designed to draw in listeners and sell them my sponsors products. I was a digital marketing professional in the making and didn’t even know it.
In 2016 I transitioned to a brand marketing strategist role with Curtis Media in Raleigh. Then I decided to really roll the dice in life and accepted the Marketing Manager role for the Carlson Center in Fairbanks, Alaska.
I was now writing website content, placing ads on social media and Google, overseeing video production for online consumption and planning large scale events.
Nobody had ever really taught me much about digital marketing, I was kind of learning on the fly. So in 2019 I enrolled in Rutgers Business School’s Masters of Science in Digital Marketing program.
I graduated in May of 2021 earning a degree with honors, magma cum laude, with a 3.95 cumulative gpa. 
While that was happening, Covid wrecked my career as a marketing professional in the arena space. I thought to further enhance my skill set that a digital marketing agency made sense and I landed an amazing opportunity at Avalaunch Media in Lehi, Utah.
Today I handle management and digital strategy for clients all over the world, plus I’m working towards becoming an adjunct professor of digital marketing, a goal of mine with obtaining my masters degree.
If I can offer you advice on your marketing strategy, send me a message and let’s talk!
I’m a competitive triathlete and marathon runner. My 2022 race schedule includes the Salt Lake City Marathon, Ironman Oregon 70.3, and Ironman Washington 70.3. I enjoy skiing and hiking in the Utah mountains as well! I love dogs, rescues in particular, and have two black lab rescue pups. I reside in South Salt Lake City, Utah and have recently become a Utah Jazz and Real Salt Lake fan.

Growth-focused Vice President Strategy and Business Development for innovative digital health software and device products. Known for building trust with fast paced teams to create strategy for healthcare products that improve the ecosystem for individuals with proven commercial launch and revenue success.  

Aanchal is the Vice President of Strategy and Business Development at Icario Health. She joined NovuHealth (now Icario) and worked with the executive team and board members to establish the near-term growth strategy and strategic plan for expansion via new market products, business development partners, and business vision. She was responsible as VP of Product Management and Marketing leading new market clients, product innovations and execution on product portfolio initiatives as Revel & Novu merged to form Icario in late 2020.

Driving strategic initiatives and partnerships/M&A, she was the Director of Corporate Strategy at Change Healthcare during the McKesson-Change merger for the Software and Analytics Business. 

Leading the roadmap for growth at Change-McKesson, she was responsible for a multi-million dollar P&L spanning a portfolio of products that served more than 100+ health system/IDN/ACO clients within hospital clinical connectivity. These products were SaaS-based solutions including Health Information Exchange (HIE), Patient Engagement platform, and FHIR-based applications. 

Developing value-based care strategy for product innovation that redefined the healthcare ecosystem leveraging clinical data, she spearheaded the initial product vision, pricing, and commercialization with clients of the first offerings on the new cloud-based analytics platform, while evangelizing the SMART on FHIR data strategy at industry conferences. 

Educated as an electrical and computer engineer and MBA graduate from Harvard Business School, her background spans experiences in the financial services industry and various medical device & digital health technologies. 

Fun fact: She co-founded a company/invention that was showcased on Shark Tank and was recently sold. Ever accidentally shrink your beloved wool sweaters? Check out the patent-pending solution, Unshrinkit.com.

I am a software engineer with a primary focus on frontend web development and education technology. I believe that technology has the power to support students and teachers in being more flexible, more intentional, more perceptive, and more engaged with each other as they handle the challenges of teaching and learning. I felt the transformative influence of technology in my own experience as a teacher, and I am convinced of the value that technology can add to the classroom.

I taught middle and upper school Latin for 11 years in RI, NV, CO, and NJ. In my last year of teaching, I attended an after-school programming class taught by two senior boys (Jonathan Tang & Oliver Barnum, to whom I am very grateful for their instruction & inspiration!). I started working on a web app that would allow my students to practice Latin forms and grammar. It changed the way I was able to differentiate instruction in class and the way students were able to practice the material independently outside of class. Having experienced firsthand the way that technology can reshape a situation, I am excited about my ongoing work on Magistrula.com and my role at AltSchool, and I am passionate about contributing to the educational community from outside the classroom.

summary:
Solving problems and noticing the details.

I have spent my whole career in the manufacturing industry.  Here I learned that the smallest detail can make or break a project.  I was taught a hands-on approach to problem solving.  I started working production lines at 18 years old and there I was taught the smallest change can impact a project in exponential ways.  This skill carried over as I started working in Tool & Die designing and building tools for production - where even the smallest detail matters.

While I was beginning my career, I attended college to earn my degree in Information Systems; a passion I hold dear.  I have installed complete networks from the ground up, taught myself how to deploy and run VoIP systems, and troubleshoot hardware issues.  Deployed CCTV systems from the older RG style to the now IP based systems.  I love to watch networks grow and how the different systems interconnect, how to secure them, and how to scale them across multiple campuses.

My experience thus far in my life has led me to be able to analyze problems from many different sides, from mechanical, to technological, and product interactions.  I have led small teams in production all the way to my current position leading several diverse crews in reaching the same goal.

Even when I go on vacation, I will view the building I am staying in admiring how the APs are deployed, what CCTV systems are deployed and their coverage, and how the building mechanicals works.  

My passions do not just lie with the mechanical and IT side either.  I am an elected official and volunteer to run as a city council member in my community.  To serve and communicate with others and hopefully bridge the gaps between viewpoints.

occupation: Piano Professor at Aeyons
headline: Concert Pianist; Adjudicator of International Music Competitions; Piano Professor at Communauté de Communes Châteaubriant - Derval
summary:
Born in Bulgaria,  Avguste Antonov has studied piano performance in Bulgaria (Dobrich), France (Ecole Normale de Paris, Conservatoire de Bordeaux Jacques Thibaud) and the United States (2000: University of Missouri-Kansas City; 2001-2004: University of Kansas; 2006-2008: Texas Christian University).

Pianist Avguste Antonov is at home in all repertoire and has a special interest for the music of the 20th and 21st century, especially American living composers. He has performed World and USA premieres at venues across North America and over the years, he has worked with composers Carter Pann, Raina Murnak, Matthew Lewis, Till Meyn, Matthew Saunders, Robert Rollin, William Vollinger and others.

Avguste Antonov has performed recitals all over the  United States, including in Colorado, Kansas, Iowa, Missouri, Florida, Pennsylvania, Texas, Ohio, South Carolina, Tennessee . He has been featured as soloist with many ensembles including the San Jose State University Wind Symphony, the San Jose Wind Symphony, the University City Symphony, the Alton Symphony Orchestra, the Tulsa Camerata, the Lakeland Community Orchestra, the Jewish Community Orchestra-Portland and the South Kansas Symphony.  Concertos performed include Schumann Piano Concerto, Rachmaninoff 2nd, McDowell 2nd, Liszt 2nd, Ravel in G, Gershwin in F,  Gershwin "Rhapsody in Blue", Carter Pann "Concerto Logic" and Matthew Saunders "Piano Concerto".

In addition to performing, Avguste Antonov is active as lecturer and and has presented lectures for the Carrollton Music Teachers Association, Frisco Music Teachers Association, Kansas Music Teachers Association, Oklahoma Music Teachers Association and Wisconsin Music Teachers Association.  He is an adjudicator for various competitions, including the ENKOR Piano Competition, the Sound Espressivo Global Competition and the Music International Grand Prix.

Previous seasons highlights include a recital at the Bulgarian Ambassador Residence in Washington, DC, the performance of Carter Pann "Concerto Logic" with the San Jose State University Wind Ensemble, a live performance for the Kansas Public Radio, the World and US Premiere of Matthew Saunders "Piano Concerto" with the University City Symphony (University City, MO) and the Lakeland Community Orchestra (Kirtland, OH). 

Since April 2019 Avguste Antonov resides in France. During the year 2019-2020, he was piano professor at the school of music  "Couleur Musique" . Starting in September 2020, he will be professor of piano and accompaniment at the Conservatoire de Châteaubriant.

occupation: Academic Advisor in the College of HS&E at North Dakota State University
headline: Academic Advisor in the College of HSE at North Dakota State University
summary:
Strengths: Achiever | Harmony | Learner | Input | Discipline
Strong Interest Inventory: S (Social), C (Conventional), E (Enterprising)

My own career path has been anything but linear. Once I was first introduced to the world of careers, I saw the gaps in career education among my peers but also myself. I had been thinking there was only one way to be successful, and I would have to struggle through it alone. But life is not linear; it is chaotic, as one decision can alter your entire reality. There is not one "right" way to enter a field and obtain a position. Not one major leads to one job for your entire career. The thought of being able to educate someone through the chaos of life while guiding them along the journey to finding a career path, provides me with fulfillment as I have made a true difference in their life. Advising a student on what courses best match their interests and exploring careers related to a major may seem small, but that aid may help them feel confident enough to apply to new positions or even achieve their dream job. Seeing the success of the individuals that I have mentored and advised makes all of the research, education, and planning worth it.

I may be contacted at aarabrahamson@gmail.com
Experience: Academic Advisor in the College of HS&E

I taken the Strength Finders Test, the result of which are below:

The Clifton StrengthsFinder measures the presence of talent in 34 categories called "themes." These themes were determined by Gallup as those that most consistently predict outstanding performance. The greater the presence of a theme of talent within a person, the more likely that person is to spontaneously exhibit those talents in day-to-day behaviors. Focusing on naturally powerful talents helps people use them as the foundation of strengths and enjoy personal, academic, and career success through consistent, near-perfect performance.

Below are my top five themes of talent, ranked in the order revealed by my responses to the Clifton StrengthsFinder.

Restorative
People who are especially talented in the Restorative theme are adept at dealing with problems. They are good at figuring out what is wrong and resolving it.

Relator
People who are especially talented in the Relator theme enjoy close relationships with others. They find deep satisfaction in working hard with friends to achieve a goal.

Intellection
People who are especially talented in the Intellection theme are characterized by their intellectual activity. They are introspective and appreciate intellectual discussions.

Strategic
People who are especially talented in the Strategic theme create alternative ways to proceed. Faced with any given scenario, they can quickly spot the relevant patterns and issues.

Responsibility
People who are especially talented in the Responsibility theme take psychological ownership of what they say they will do. They are committed to stable values such as honesty and loyalty.

A feature flag is a conditional code statement placed into your code that can toggle a feature on or off.

Many organizations also use our UI to help manage technical debt that accumulates with development.

occupation: HPC Software Architect at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory
headline: HPC Software Architect at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory
summary:
I work with teams of physicists, computer scientists, and applied mathematicians on high performance, massively parallel, multi-physics simulation codes.

The majority of my time is spent assisting code teams with refactoring their algorithms and code infrastructure to take advantage of the heterogenous architecture in the Sierra supercomputer, sited at LLNL.  Sierra is one of the fastest supercomputers in the world, rated at 120-150 petaflops.

Work is also progressing on adapting these codes to run on the next generation of supercomputer, El Capitan.  This architecture will provide NNSA with it's first exascale system, providing a 10x performance jump over Sierra.

If you are interested in a career or a summer student internship working on some of the fastest supercomputers in the world, on the bleeding edge, feel free to contact me or check out our jobs site at http://jobs.llnl.gov

occupation: Director Of Software Development at EML
headline: Director of Software Development at EML Payments
summary:
I'm a software developer and manager, focused on building great software. What is great software you may ask? Well, it is:

- Secure
- In production
- There to fulfill the needs of users - and behave as they would expect it to behave
- Resistant to failures - it should expect failures in its dependencies and continue to process
- Resilient to failures - if a catastrophic failure is unavoidable, then it should fail gracefully and be monitor-able
- Testable and tested, through unit, integration, and manual testing
- Simple and maintainable, following SOLID principles
- Aware and contains or defines its external dependencies
- Documented for its users, creators, and maintainers
- Delivered on time, and in budget

What matters most in this is people. People build and use software, and it should make everyone's lives better, not worse. It takes a village to make a product, and I strive to be the best villager I can be, fulfilling whatever role is needed.

My curiosity, empathy, and analytical approach to life followed me from childhood into adulthood. My time at VT & NSS fostered these character traits and gave me a desire to utilize these traits in the professional world. 

After graduating from VT, I found a job in healthcare doing hands-on patient care as a CNA. Working with people that needed help to do almost everything fulfilled my desire to be compassionate & empathetic and provided me with a sense of purpose. 

Four years later, curiosity propelled me to pursue a path that would fulfill my desire to understand how things work. I became a commercial/residential plumber; within 6 months of starting, I was promoted from helper to technician and was sent into the field with the expectation of solving plumbing issues on my own. I utilized my knowledge and analytical approach to give the customer the best service I could provide. As much as I enjoyed my time as a plumber, I found myself craving a more dynamic challenge; I needed to fulfill my curiosity and analytical mindset.

I was first introduced to programming one night a few years ago using StumbeUpon. It brought me to CodeAcademy. I found myself staying up way too late learning about this world completely new to me.  Studying programming became a hobby; it remained in my mind and eventually drove me to pursue a career in software development. 

I discovered Nashville Software School and found it to be a place where my analytical approach and curiosity is continually fulfilled and reignited everyday. NSS also became a place where I can practice empathy with my classmates by learning their perspectives, being a trustworthy, helpful teammate, and showing attention and understanding. I have no doubt this path I chose will be anything but challenging and fulfilling providing me with the best opportunity to utilize and grow my character traits.

occupation: Business Analyst at Mindcurv
headline: Business Analyst
summary:
Desde que era pequeño supe que los ordenadores serían mi pasión. Todavía recuerdo mi primer contacto con "uno", en casa de un vecino, jugando al Trivial Pursuit en su Amiga.
Mientras jugaba todos y cada uno de los juegos que tenía mi vecino, me di cuenta de que el inglés sería una herramienta totalmente necesaria si alguna vez quería trabajar con ordenadores.
Cuando me di cuenta de que podría aprenderlo por mi cuenta, entendí que no debería ser sólo eso lo que aprendiese por mi cuenta, así que me puse manos a la obra para aprender otras "skills" que me ayudasen. 
No tuve la oportunidad de ir a la universidad pero me las he arreglado para aprender lo suficiente para poder relacionarme de igual a igual con la gente de este mundillo.
Si me lo puedo permitir, todos los días intentaré aprender un poquito de algo, lo que sea.
Aquel jovenzuelo queda ya muy lejos, hoy soy otro tipo de persona, igual de inquieta y con el mismo afán por aprender pero mucho más comprometido, perfeccionista, minucioso, entregado, dedicado, buen compañero y, por supuesto, humilde (menudo lugar para poner este adjetivo, ¿a que sí? Pero es la verdad).

Me gusta trabajar como me gusta tratar a las personas, de forma sincera y honesta. Esto hace que mi interlocutor se sienta lo suficientemente cómodo como para permitirme ayudarle con sus problemas.

He pasado por muchos puestos técnicos a lo largo de mi carrera, soporte, customer success, analista, etc. 

Todo lo anterior me permite:
- Basar mis decisiones en datos sin dejar de lado el instinto.
- Saber que el cliente o usuario es el centro de mi trabajo.
- Hacer que su satisfacción sea mi satisfacción y sus victorias mis victorias.
- Llegar a conclusiones usando un idioma técnico o ejecutivo e informar a los usuarios o clientes en su mismo lenguaje para que entiendan y aprendan un poquillo si les apetece.
- Ser un remanso de paz cuando llega la adversidad, que siempre llega.
- Prestar especial atención al detalle (Tantísimo que he conseguido convertirlo en mi hobby).
- Entender que no hay tecnología fuera de mi alcance.
- Dominar cualquier cosa que quiera hacer.
- Tomar decisiones creativas.
- Trabajar todos y cada uno de los días con una sonrisa e intentar que quien me rodea se sienta igual.

Mis especialidades son:
- Soporte.
- Customer Success.
- Product Owner/Manager.
- Team building.

occupation: Engineer I at Seagate Technology
headline: Engineer I at Seagate Technology
summary:
Worked on numerous Engineering teams with various projects with topics in computer hardware device development though VHDL. Device Firmware development though C. Information processing though java using various computer science algorithms. Electrical engineering fundamentals. 
 
Developed a interest in computer hardware and the architecture behind this hardware though school. 

Favorite school project: MIPS Processor
One of my favorite projects in school was when I was tasked with building a MIPS processor from the ground up using logic design coupled with VHDL and Verilog. The processor was able to ability to properly execute assembly code and was also fully pipelined to allow for processing of five instructions at a time. I also worked with forwarding information within the pipeline itself to boost processor performance by shortening instruction processing time that use the processors critical path. This project was done though ModelSim which not only allowed for simulation of these hardware description languages, but also enabled me to write test benches for various different components and verify their logic. This project has influenced my recent interest to build a RISC-V processor using the same VHDL and Verilog methods.
